ize has enacted four laws related to cybercrime, namely: The Telecommunication Act, Electronic Evidence Act, Intellectual Property Act and Interception of Communication Act. Without comprehensive criminal law, however, law enforcement and the judiciary face difficulty effectively prosecuting cybercrime.  Accordingly, although there is no binding agreement for the disclosure of breaches in cyber security, government and the private sector cooperate to report and address cyberattacks, and while statistics are limited, the Government of Belize has noted an increase in incidents in recent years.\r\n\r\nIn response to growing threats to cyber security in the region, government has begun to promote strengthened security standards and technology among agencies and CNI operators; however, stakeholders have not formulated response plans or other crisis-management policies in relation to CNI protection. \r\n\r\nWith 31.7% internet penetration, much of Belizean society has not developed a cyber security mind-set.  In order to raise awareness of cyber security issues, the Belize Police Department participates in the an annual \u201cICT Road Show\u201d, which is hosted by the Ministry of Energy, Science & Technology, Public Utilities (MESTPU). The BPD uses this platform to educate communities on both the opportunities and risks of cyber space. This year, with the support of the private sector, academia and other stakeholders, the Government of Belize plans to hold its First Annual Cyber Security Week. Further, Belize also hopes to launch the Stop. Think. Connect Public Education campaign by the end of 2015. There are currently no degree programs in cyber security in the country\u2019s universities, but some private-sector companies do offer training programs.","population":"340844","people_with_computer":"0","people_with_internet":"90939","mobile_phone_subscriptions":"173830","maturity_levels":{"1":"1","2":"1","3":"1","4":"1","5":"1","6":"1","7":"2","8":"2","9":"1","10":"1","11"