of the TTDF (Regiment, Coast Guard and Air Guard) who share cyber-defense responsibilities. This year, Trinidad and Tobago will officially launch the country\u2019s first National Computer Incident Response Team (TTCSIRT), which will work closely with the OAS, ITU, and other international organizations to develop incident response capacity. \r\n\r\nMany owners and operators of critical national infrastructure have crisis response or reporting mechanisms in place, particularly those within the private sector. The National Cyber Security Strategy calls for building competency among key stakeholders and developing incident management measures. Furthermore, adherence to international standards such as ISO 27001 is becoming widespread across government, telecommunications providers, security services, and the financial sector.  \r\n\r\nThe Minister of National Security has introduced a Cybercrime Bill to Parliament for enactment, which is meant to repeal the existing Computer Misuse Act and replace it with a more comprehensive legal framework for dealing with cybercrime. The country has also a data protection law, but it is only partially proclaimed. The Cybercrime Unit of the Trinidad and Tobago Police Service (TTPS) handles cyber crime investigation and is equipped with a digital forensics lab. The successful prosecution of cyber crime, however, successful prosecution of cybercrime can be difficult, as courtrooms often lack digital-evidence capacities and there is no framework in place requiring the private sector to disclose cyber incidents.\r\n\r\nThe Ministry of National Security has initiated its public awareness campaign. Additionally, the Ministry of Science and Technology and various public and private organizations, such as the University of Trinidad and Tobago (UTTI) and the Telecommunications Authority of Trinidad and Tobago (TATT), have joined efforts to conduct workshops and other programs aimed at educating the public about cyber security. The private sect