, CERTuy provides statistics on cyber attacks and issues alerts on emerging risks. Uruguay also relies on incident analysis and response from the National Telecommunications Administration\u2019s CSIRT-ANTEL, which was founded in 2005 to address issues related to cellular phone data and services.  \r\n\r\nThe Government of Uruguay formally manages security for critical national infrastructure and shares information on CNI assets and vulnerabilities. It is also currently strengthening security and employee privacy standards. Uruguay is a regional leader in security software development and a marketplace for new technologies and cyber crime insurance. Government agencies execute risk management exercises to effectively coordinate response assets. In cases of emergency, the National Emergency System would issue redundancy communication. \r\n\r\nThe Computer Crime Unit of the National Police is the agency responsible for investigating cyber crime. It maintains a digital forensic laboratory and receives capacity building support from the OAS and other organizations. In recent years, the unit has detected an increase in cyber crime. The Government of Uruguay has drafted a legal framework for cyber security and has adopted Law No 18.331 on Data Protection. However, it has not adopted criminal law specific to cyber crime and has no disclosure mechanisms in place for the private sector. Uruguay is party to MERCOSUR Digital, which aims to normalize e-commerce and cyber security across member states. Furthermore, major private-sector areas and the banking industry are well-educated on both cyber threats and strategies to protect against them.\r\n\r\nAcademia and the public and private sectors offer opportunities for training and education in cyber security, and the government has been working to bolster cyber security educational initiatives. It has also launched national awareness-raising campaigns, namely \u201cConnect yourself safely\u201d, led by CERTuy, and \u201cYour data has worth. Protect it\u201d, led by AGESIC. Uruguay has also partnered with the US Department of Homeland Security\u2019s STOP.THINK.CONNECT campaign.","population":"3332972","people_with_computer":"0","people_with_internet":"2017280","mobile_phone_subscriptions":"5366084","maturity_levels":{"1":"3","2":"4","3":"2","4":"2","5":"3","6":"4","7":"4","8":"3","9":"3","10":"4","11":"4","12":"5","13":"4","14":"5","15":"4","16":"3","17":"5","18":"3","19":"4","20":"2","21":"4","22":"5","23":"1","24":"2","25":"2","26":"2","27":"2","28":"1","29":"2","30":"3","31":"2","32":"3","33":"5","34":"4","35":"4","36":"4","37":"3","38":"3","39":"2","40":"2","41":"3","42":"2","43":"2","44":"2","45":"2","46":"3","47":"3","48":"2","49":"3"}},{"id":"32","code":"ve","name":"Venezuela","excerpt":"Venezuela\u2019s lead agency for national cyber security, the National System for Cyber Telematics Incident Management (known as VenCERT) performs multiple roles, namely: responding to cyber incidents, keeping statistics on cyberattack trends and evaluating and strengthening national cyber security infrastructure. As cyberattacks, including government-website defacements and DDoS attacks, continue to increase in the country, VenCERT\u2019s response capacity has been limited.  It has recently increased its staff size, but requires new techniques and tools to keep pace with emerging cyber threats.","description":"Venezuela\u2019s lead agency for national cyber security, the National System for Cyber Telematics Incident Management (known as VenCERT) performs multiple roles, namely: responding to cyber incidents, keeping statistics on cyberattack trends and evaluating and strengthening national cyber security infrastructure. As cyberattacks, including government-website defacements and DDoS attacks, continue to increase in the country, VenCERT\u2019s response capacity has been limited.  It has recently increased its staff size, but requires new techniques and tools to keep pace with emerging cyber threats. \r\n\r\nVenezuela has neither a national cyber security policy nor a cyber-defense strategy, but it has adopted a number of laws that together constitute a comprehensive legal framework for cybercrime. Special Law against Computer Crime (Law 37.313) was enacted in 2001, and the National Assembly has recently passed the Interoperability Act (2012) and Info-Government Act (2013) which establish standards and norms for electronic exchange, as well as some procedural law. Although the Constitution provides for freedom of expression, there are no laws in place dealing specifically with privacy or freedom of expression online. \r\n\r\nThree agencies form the country\u2019s primary response to cybercrime: the Cybercrime Division of the Center for Scientific, Penal and Criminal Investigations (CICPC), the National Center for Digital Forensics (CENIF) and the Superintendency of Electronic Certification Services (SUSCERTE). Government routinely provides for training for CICPC personnel to ensure that they are up to date on cybercrime trends. \r\n\r\nThrough its plan Secure Homeland (Patria Segura), SUSCERTE formally manages security for CNI technology, issues digital certificates and keeps statistics on incidents. CNI operators have begun to adopt security measures to comply with international standards, and have basic capacity to protect infrastructure from cyberattacks. \r\n\r\nIn addition to issuing digital certificates for government and CNI technology and keeping statistics, SUSCERTE has lead the \u201cInformation Security Begins with You\u201d campaign, which aims to educate the public on cyber security through talks, fora and workshops. A number of cyber security and cybercrime degree programs are also available in the country. Nevertheless, a lack of societal awareness of cyber security and limited privacy protection for citizens continue to present challenges to Venezuela\u2019s cyber security regime.","population":"28868486","people_with_computer":"0","people_wi